      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "19695e36",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "**Insight:** Key correlations — xG↔Scored (0.63) and xGA↔Conceded (0.63) are the strongest, confirming xG features are top predictors. Possession↔PPDA (-0.64) shows high-possession teams press more. Most features have moderate independence, meaning they each add unique information to a model."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "85f323a7",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 12) Final Takeaways\n",
        "\n",
        "**Description:** Key conclusions from this EDA run.\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Overall outcomes insight:** The dataset is moderately imbalanced: home-team wins and losses are similar, while draws are less frequent.\n",
        "- **Home/away insight:** Here, rows are stored as home-team perspective (`Team` home, `Opponent` away), so this notebook reports home-side outcomes directly. A strict home-vs-away causal comparison needs a separate away-perspective table or fixture-level merge.\n",
        "- **xG realism insight:** `xG` and `xGA` show strong positive relationships with `Scored` and `Conceded`, so they are reliable base features.\n",
        "- **Fatigue impact insight:** Teams with recent non-league matches (last 7 days) show weaker result mix on average, suggesting congestion may hurt performance.\n",
        "- **Weekly goals trend insight:** Weekly goals fluctuate, but moving-average trends capture broader rhythm better than single-week spikes.\n",
        "- **End-of-season pressure insight:** Late-season matches show a slightly tighter profile (more draws), consistent with pressure and cautious game states.\n",
        "- **Features to prioritize next:** Keep `xG`, `xGA`, `Scored`, `Conceded`, fatigue bucket, and late-season phase; treat home-vs-away as a data-modeling limitation to solve in a future dataset merge."
      ]
    }
